HEADWORD: Periphery
<hw>Pe*riph"er*y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Peripheries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>peripheria</ets>, Gr. <grk>perife`reia</grk>; <grk>peri`</grk>
around + <grk>fe`rein</grk> to bear, carry: cf. F.
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧riph⟦eacute⟧rie</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The outside
or superficial portions of a body; the surface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>The circumference of a circle,
ellipse, or other figure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Periphrase</ent>⟦br⟧
